issue.title: Can't install with Composer?!?!
issue.body:
I went to use your wonderful library and was like, I'll install it through Composer so I did:

`composer require asgrim/side-effect`

But, Composer was like "We don't know what that package is."

And, I was like... "whaaaaa?"

So, you should absolutely put this on packagist.

issue.title: Provide more details on expected implementation of custom attributes
issue.body:
With the release of 1.5 Annotated Container allows the implementation of custom Attributes to replace what is provided out-of-the-box. While very useful functionality it also presents an opportunity for end-users to shoot themselves in the foot. The various Attribute interfaces have other caveats expected of them that can't be easily defined in an interface. Namely:

- They should be marked with an `#[Attribute]`
- The target of that Attribute is intended to be specific, i.e. it wouldn't make sense to add a ServiceAttribute to a class property or an InjectAttribute to a class.
- They should or should not be repeatable. Most Attributes are not intended to be repeated, for example it doesn't make sense to repeat a ServiceAttribute. Others are, it does make sense to repeat an InjectAttribute.

We should determine a system to properly communicate these details to the end-user. Descriptive attributes on each interface could be a good approach. For example, create a `#[ShouldTargetClass]` Attribute and add that to the `ServiceAttribute` interface.

Note, that this is _NOT_ taking place of any Logical Constraints that might be added to address this potential issue.

issue.title: Ensure Configuration objects implementing an interface can be used as a concrete alias
issue.body: It might be that a library needs a configuration object but requests an interface. In these situations users implementing that library may want to use a `#[Configuration]` to satisfy that dependency. This is currently not possible but should be supported.
